<div id="review_1172856417" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1172856417" />
    <a title="Anne Martin" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/32648608-anne-martin"><img alt="Anne Martin" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1418692433p2/32648608.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1172856417?book_show_action=true">Jan 18, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Anne Martin" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Anne Martin" href="/user/show/32648608-anne-martin">Anne Martin</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781634132121" href="/book/show/23974760-the-widow-or-widower-next-door">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1172856417" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5600743999168662061">It is impossible not to be moved by the stores this book contains. A group of people speak about one of the most vulnerable time of their lives, the weeks, months or years following the death of their spouse. They don&apos;t try to describe their sadness, as they believe no one can understand the pain, the emptiness, the lack of stable points to rebuild a life.<br/>Actually, I think most people understand quite well, as after childhood, very few of us escape losing someone they love deeply. I lost my fath</span>
  <span id="freeText5600743999168662061" style="display:none">It is impossible not to be moved by the stores this book contains. A group of people speak about one of the most vulnerable time of their lives, the weeks, months or years following the death of their spouse. They don't try to describe their sadness, as they believe no one can understand the pain, the emptiness, the lack of stable points to rebuild a life.<br />Actually, I think most people understand quite well, as after childhood, very few of us escape losing someone they love deeply. I lost my father at 20, my mother at 29, and my sister at 32. Do you think it s better than to lose a husband? It means that at an age where most people have a financial background from their parents, when you want to learn about your family, your roots, when you think you still have 10 or 20 years to be someone's daughter, to be love unconditionally, - it was all gone!<br />I understand how hard it is to let go of the persons who shared your life for years or decades, how the hole left will never be filled.<br />And you must cope with whatever cards you have been dealt, no second chances.<br />So, I wish the book would have extended from the widows and widowers to any person who grieves the loss of loved ones.<br />I regret the author, Mary Lee could not have synthesized the few pages written by each of those persons who had lost their mates. It would have changed the book from a touching collection of despair stories to a higher level.<br />Death and pain are the most horrible experiences we have to get through. And for those who were upset or irritated by clumsy comments, don't forget words go out fast, too fast... and remember the grieving one does not always help. A friend has lost his wife a few months ago. We called a few times, invited him for dinner, asked him f his days were not awfully long, and were told he was quite busy and did not have time to go out. What to do, then? of course, he lies a bit, but how can you drag him somewhere?<br />And what about the divorced one who feels like a moral widow(er)? left by his mate without understanding why? Or people who lost kids? Life can be very tough.<br />Anyway, the book makes you think, which was its purpose. But it would be worth a deeper study, with more nuances., Not all widow(er)s are desperate. Some find consolation in things their mate dd not let them do or have (the pets), some may be relieved because the suffering of the other is finished. Some may be in a catastrophic financial situation, and yes, it matters! Dig deeper, Mary Lee, it is worth it.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5600743999168662061" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


