<div id="review_1219290359" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1219290359" />
    <a title="Ted Tayler" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/23827747-ted-tayler"><img alt="Ted Tayler" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1445264611p2/23827747.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1219290359?book_show_action=true">Mar 05, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ted Tayler" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ted Tayler" href="/user/show/23827747-ted-tayler">Ted Tayler</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781634132121" href="/book/show/23974760-the-widow-or-widower-next-door">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1219290359" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10367341957822594994">&quot;an emotional roller coaster that the death of a loved one forces us to ride&quot;<br/><br/>All of us have to deal with losing someone at some point in our lives; if there hasn&apos;t been a book like this written before then it should have been. Mary Lee documents her own personal experiences alongside a whole series of accounts from other people trying to cope with their grief after the death of a loved one. Initially the format works well and I recognised many of the anecdotes! I hadn&apos;t read them anywhere else; </span>
  <span id="freeText10367341957822594994" style="display:none">"an emotional roller coaster that the death of a loved one forces us to ride"<br /><br />All of us have to deal with losing someone at some point in our lives; if there hasn't been a book like this written before then it should have been. Mary Lee documents her own personal experiences alongside a whole series of accounts from other people trying to cope with their grief after the death of a loved one. Initially the format works well and I recognised many of the anecdotes! I hadn't read them anywhere else; it was pretty much what I experienced myself when my parents died.<br />I really wanted to rate this book more highly, because the motives behind writing it are so laudable, but the Q/A format for the latter parts of the book was a trifle patchy. Why those questions? Weren't there others that might have provided a comprehensive check list for a bereaved spouse to have by their side as a reference book? Overall though, a book I'm glad I had the opportunity to read.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10367341957822594994" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


